---
import Base from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Header from "../components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
---
<Base title="The Problem"><Fragment slot="header"><Header /></Fragment>

  <section class="relative pt-28 pb-16 overflow-hidden bg-subtle-grid" style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,#fafaf9 0%,#ffffff 30%,#ede9fe 100%)">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 lg:px-8 relative">
      <div class="max-w-2xl"><p class="sl">The problem</p><h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-heading font-bold text-stone-900 leading-tight mb-5">Academic software for genomics is broken</h1><p class="text-lg text-stone-600 max-w-xl">The tools that power genomic discovery are built by PhD students, not software engineers. Funded by grants, not maintenance. Here's why that's a crisis.</p></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="py-20">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-12 items-start">
        <div class="space-y-5 text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">
          <p>Genomic research runs on software built by a broken system. Every major tool, pipeline, and platform in use today was written by a PhD student or postdoc as part of their research. It was built to answer a specific question, get a publication, and graduate. Once that student leaves — and they always leave — the tool enters a half-life of decay.</p>
          <p>No one is paid to maintain it. No one is accountable when it breaks. The community forks it, patches it, and moves on. Now there are five incompatible versions of the same tool, none of them well-documented, all of them maintained by someone's goodwill.</p>
          <p>This is not how infrastructure works in any other domain. Imagine if AWS were maintained by graduate students who graduated every two years. That's the state of genomic software.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-stone-50 border border-stone-100 rounded-xl p-8 space-y-4">
          <h3 class="font-heading font-semibold text-stone-900 text-sm uppercase tracking-wider">A concrete example</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">A research group builds a popular variant annotation tool. The PhD student who wrote it graduates and leaves academia entirely. Within two years, three other labs have forked it to fix bugs in their specific use case. None of the forks merge back. The original repository becomes read-only. A sequencing center evaluating infrastructure finds five competing versions, none of which they can adopt confidently. The tool is free, but the cost of choosing wrong is higher than paying for something maintained.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="py-20 bg-stone-50 border-y border-stone-100 reveal">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="max-w-xl mb-10"><p class="sl">Root causes</p><h2 class="text-3xl font-heading font-bold text-stone-900">Why it stays broken</h2></div>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-5">
        <div class="card"><h3 class="font-heading font-semibold text-stone-900 mb-2">Incentives are misaligned</h3><p class="text-sm text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">Academia rewards publications and citations, not maintained software. A new tool with a new paper gets more credit than maintaining an existing one for a decade. There is zero career incentive for ongoing support.</p></div>
        <div class="card"><h3 class="font-heading font-semibold text-stone-900 mb-2">Standards without implementation</h3><p class="text-sm text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">GA4GH and other bodies produce excellent spec documents. But the gap between a spec and a working, tested, documented reference implementation is enormous — and largely unfunded. Standards that don't ship might as well not exist.</p></div>
        <div class="card"><h3 class="font-heading font-semibold text-stone-900 mb-2">Competition over interoperability</h3><p class="text-sm text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">Every research group wants their tool to be the one people use. This drives a proliferation of overlapping tools, not collaboration on shared infrastructure. The community loses when every lab reinvents the same wheel.</p></div>
        <div class="card"><h3 class="font-heading font-semibold text-stone-900 mb-2">No long-term funding model</h3><p class="text-sm text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">Grants fund building, not maintaining. Academia cannot afford to employ software engineers at market rates. The result is software that works today and breaks tomorrow, with no one paid to fix it.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="py-20">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="max-w-xl mb-10"><p class="sl">The gap</p><h2 class="text-3xl font-heading font-bold text-stone-900">What's missing from the picture</h2></div>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-5">
        <div class="card"><h3 class="font-heading font-semibold text-stone-900 mb-2">Accountability</h3><p class="text-sm text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">When a pipeline breaks at a sequencing center, who do you call? The PI who wrote the grant? The student who graduated two years ago? There's no vendor, no SLA, no one whose job depends on keeping the software working.</p></div>
        <div class="card"><h3 class="font-heading font-semibold text-stone-900 mb-2">Documentation</h3><p class="text-sm text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">Most academic software ships with the README that got the paper accepted. After that, documentation is a luxury no one has time for. Production deployment requires docs that don't assume you wrote the code.</p></div>
        <div class="card"><h3 class="font-heading font-semibold text-stone-900 mb-2">Longevity</h3><p class="text-sm text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">A sequencing center plans on a 5-10 year horizon for infrastructure decisions. A PhD project has a 2-4 year horizon. These timelines are fundamentally incompatible, and the centers lose every time.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="relative py-20 overflow-hidden" style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,#5b21b6,#4c1d95,#3b0764)">
    <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-subtle-grid opacity-[0.08]" />
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 lg:px-8 text-center relative">
      <div class="max-w-xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-heading font-bold text-white mb-3">This is fixable</h2>
        <p class="text-cobalt-200 leading-relaxed mb-8">We build genomic infrastructure the right way — open source, engineer-maintained, funded by support contracts, not grants. The same model that works for every other layer of the software stack.</p>
        <a href="/services" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-8 py-3 bg-white hover:bg-stone-50 text-stone-800 font-medium rounded-xl transition-all active:scale-[0.97]">See how we work →</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

<Fragment slot="footer"><Footer /></Fragment></Base>